Background

In the data folder, you will find data about shark incidents in California between 1950-2022. The data are from: State of California- Shark Incident Database.

Load the libraries

library("tidyverse")
library("janitor")

Load the data

Run the following code chunk to import the data. In this chunk, I am removing NAs.

sharks <- 
  read_csv("data/SharkIncidents_1950_2022_220302.csv", 
           na=c("NA", "N/A", "Unknown", "NOT COUNTED", "", " ")) %>% 
  clean_names()

Questions

  1. Are there any hotspots for shark incidents in California? Show the top five counties with the most incidents.
sharks %>% 
  count(county) %>% 
  slice_max(n, n=5) 
## # A tibble: 6  2
##   county            n
##   <chr>         <int>
## 1 San Diego        25
## 2 Humboldt         20
## 3 San Mateo        19
## 4 Santa Barbara    19
## 5 Marin            16
## 6 Monterey         16
#San Diego and Humboldt counties seem to be hotspots as they are the only 2 places that break the 20 incident count
  1. Make a plot that shows the total number of incidents per county.
sharks %>% 
  count(county) %>% 
  slice_max(n, n=5) %>% #assuming graph is wanted for only top 5 counties, if not then I wouldve done same but without slice_max
  ggplot(mapping=aes(y=n, x=county, fill=county))+
  geom_col()+
  labs(title = "Total Number of incidents per County",
       y="Number of Incidents",
       x="County")+
  coord_flip()

  1. Are there months of the year when incidents are more likely to occur? Make a plot that shows the total number of incidents by month. Which month has the highest number of incidents?
sharks %>% 
  count(month)
## # A tibble: 12  2
##    month     n
##    <dbl> <int>
##  1     1     8
##  2     2     4
##  3     3     5
##  4     4     7
##  5     5    16
##  6     6    14
##  7     7    27
##  8     8    31
##  9     9    34
## 10    10    36
## 11    11    16
## 12    12    13
sharks %>% 
  mutate(month=as.factor(month)) %>% 
  count(month) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y=n, x=month, fill=month))+
  geom_col()+
  labs(title="Number of Incidents Every Month",
       x="Month by its Date Number",
       y="Number of Incidents")

  1. Is there a time of day when most attacks occur? Make a plot that shows the total number of incidents by time of day. Which time of day has the highest number of incidents?

  1. How do the number and types of injuries compare by county? Make a table that shows the number of injury types by county. Which county has the highest number incidents? (hint: your table should be in wide format)

  1. Use the table from #5 to make a plot that shows the total number of incidents by county.
sharks %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=county, y=injury, fill = injury))+
  geom_col(position = "dodge")+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title = "Total Number of Incidents by County")

  1. In the data, mode refers to a type of activity. Which activity is associated with the highest number of incidents?
sharks %>% 
  count(mode)
## # A tibble: 8  2
##   mode                    n
##   <chr>               <int>
## 1 Freediving             36
## 2 Hookah Diving          10
## 3 Kayaking / Canoeing    30
## 4 Paddleboarding          7
## 5 Scuba Diving           20
## 6 Surfing / Boarding     85
## 7 Swimming               22
## 8 Walking in shallow      1
#Surfing/Boarding is associated with the highest amount of incidents
  1. Make a plot that compares the number of incidents by activity.
sharks %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=mode, fill = mode))+
  geom_bar(position = "dodge")+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title = "Number of Incidents by Activity",
       x="Activity")

  1. Which shark species is involved in the highest number of incidents?
sharks %>% 
  count(species)
## # A tibble: 12  2
##    species          n

## 11 blue             1

#Great White Sharks make up the overwhelming majority of incidents
  1. Are all incidents involving Great Whites fatal? Make a plot that shows the number and types of incidents for Great Whites only.
sharks %>% 
  filter(species=="White") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=species, fill = injury))+
  geom_bar(position = "dodge")+
  labs(title = "Number of Each Type of Incident for Great White Sharks",
       x="Injury Type")
